OK, let&#39;s look at this:

    .then(
            (data, err) =&gt; (ctx.body = data),
            (err) =&gt; {
                ctx.response.status = 404;
                ctx.body = err;
            }
     );

1. It&#39;s passing two fat arrow functions to `.then()`.  The first is a function to be called if the promise is resolved, the second is a function to be called if it&#39;s rejected.  Logically, the structure of this is `.then(resolveCalback, rejectCallback)`.
2. The first fat arrow function has two arguments, `(data, err)`.  That&#39;s wrong.  With any standard promise implementation, there is only one argument ever passed to a `.then()` handler.  Fortunately, the implementation does not use the second argument which would always be `undefined` anyway.
3. That first fat arrow function just moves the resolved value from `data` to `ctx.body`.  Apparently, the caller of the function that returns this promise will look for the resolved value in `ctx.body`.
4. The second fat arrow function is also setting up the `ctx` object with a status and error value.  And, importantly, it is NOT rethrowing or returning a rejected promise.  So, it&#39;s changing the promise from rejected to resolved.  So, the caller will only ever get a resolved promise from this function and will apparently have to examine `ctx.response.status` to know if there is an error or not.

If the fat arrow functions are confusing you, then this snippet of code could be expressed like this using regular functions:

    .then(function(data) {
        ctx.body = data;
        return data;
    }, function(err) {
        ctx.response.status = 404;
        ctx.body = err;
    });

-------------

&gt; Does data and err stand for resolve and reject here?

No.  See my second point above.  Only `data` is valid and it contains the resolved value of the promise.  Having `err` as an argument to that first clalback is a programming error.  It is not passed there.  The reject callback is the second callback function.

&gt; Normally in promises there is a function call after .then so I am a bit confused about this situation here.

These are fat arrow functions (a different type of function declaration).  So, there are two functions being passed to like `.then(fn1, fn2)`.  You can read about fat arrow functions [here on MDN][1] and [here on SitePoint][2].  Their main purpose is a shortcut syntax and a different treatment for the value of `this` inside the function.  In this case, the programmer likely used them for the shorter syntax since there are no references to `this`.


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Functions/Arrow_functions
  [2]: https://www.sitepoint.com/es6-arrow-functions-new-fat-concise-syntax-javascript/

