Horizontal centering of elements in CSS is fairly easy. Assuming your centered elements are wrapped in a div, which should be centered within its parent element, this should work (using flexbox):

```
.parent-div {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
}
```

I recommend using this rather than `margin: auto`, since it&#39;s easy to vertically center (`align-items: center`), as well as short. It also doesn&#39;t require any CSS for the wrapper div, saving time and space.

I see a lot of problems resulting from the `[UIImage imageWithCIImage:]` initializer. The main problem being that a `CIImage` does not actually contain any bitmap data. It needs to be rendered by a `CIContext` first. So the target you assign the `UIImage` to needs to _know_ that it is backed by a `CIImage` that still needs rendering. Usually `UIImageView` handles this well, but I wouldn&#39;t trust it too much.

What you can do instead is to render the image yourself into a bitmap (`CGImage`) and initialize the `UIImage` with that instead. You need a `CIContext` for that, which I recommend you create somewhere outside this method _once_ and re-use it every time you need to render an image (it&#39;s an expensive object):

    self.context = [CIContext context];

Then in your method, you render the image like this:

    CGImageRef cgImage = [self.context createCGImage:filtered_image fromRect:[filtered_image extent]];
    UIImage* result_image = [UIImage imageWithCGImage:cgImage];

